respStmt.name: Murshid al-Kātib
مرشد الكاتب
The calligrapher Murshid al-Kātib came from Shiraz (Iran), and his name appears on a number of extant manuscripts (see bibliogrpahy, Richard, Splendeurs, p. 133).

notesStmt.note: This manuscript is an illustrated copy of the well-known poem recounting the platonic love story between Mihr (the Sun), the son of Shāhpūr, and his vizier's son Mushtarī (Jupiter). The story of 90 chapters was composed by Muḥammad ibn Aḥmad ‘Aṣṣār Tabrīzī (d. 784 AH / 1382 CE). The present copy was written in nasta‘līq script by Murshid al-Kātib in 881 AH / 1476 CE. Considering the number of surviving manuscripts in which this calligrapher’s name is found, it seems he was particularly prolific. The present codex is illustrated with nine paintings. The gold-brushed leather binding with doublures of red leather decorated with filigree work is original to the manuscript.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

colophon.note: qad tamma ʿalá yad al-ʿabd al-ḍaʿīf Murshid al-Kātib fī shahr Ramaḍān li-sanat 881 /1/

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in gold and black

handDesc.handNote: Written in nastaʿlīq script in black with chapter headings in gold on an illuminated ground

decoDesc.decoNote: Nine illustrations (fols. 17b, 79b, 110a, 121a, 151b, 166b, 184a, 190a, and 214a); double-page illuminated incipit (fols. 2b-3a); chapter headings in gold on an illuminated ground; framing lines in gold and black

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated incipit
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illuminated incipit with inscriptions in the upper and lower panels in New Abbasid (broken cursive) style, reading al-ʿuẓmah li-LLāh and al-qudrah li-Llāh, respectively.

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated incipit
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated incipit with inscriptions in the upper and lower panels in New Abbasid (broken cursive) style, reading al-ʿuẓmah li-LLāh and al-qudrah li-Llāh, respectively.

decoNote.title: King Shāhpūr and his vizier, Dastūr, visit a hermit
decoNote.note: King Shāhpūr and his vizier, Dastūr, are depicted kissing the hand and foot of a hermit. Such gestures show deep respect for the wise man who has renounced the material world.

decoNote.title: Mushtarī kneels at the feet of Mihr in the presence of courtiers
decoNote.note: Mushtarī (Jupiter), who is the son of the vizier, kneels at the feet of Mihr (the Sun), the son of King Shāhpūr.

decoNote.title: Mihr sailing to India in search of Mushtarī
decoNote.note: Driven by deep affection, Mihr sails to India in search of Mushtarī.

Mihr and Nāhīd, King Kayvān's daughter, on their wedding night
